SUIS_1: SUIS - When going to a new place, I prefer directions that include detailed descriptions of landmarks (such as the size, shape and color of a gas station) in addition to their names.
SUIS_2: SUIS - If I catch a glance of a car that is partially hidden behind bushes, I automatically “complete it,” seeing the entire car in my mind’s eye.
SUIS_3: SUIS - If I am looking for new furniture in a store, I always visualize what the furniture would look like in particular places in my home.
SUIS_4: SUIS - I prefer to read novels that lead me easily to visualize where the characters are and what they are doing instead of novels that are difficult to visualize.
SUIS_5: SUIS - When I think about visiting a relative, I almost always have a clear mental picture of him or her.
SUIS_6: SUIS - When relatively easy technical material is described clearly in a text, I find illustrations distracting because they interfere with my ability to visualize the material.
SUIS_7: SUIS - If someone were to tell me two-digit numbers to add (e.g., 24 and 31), I would visualize them in order to add them.
SUIS_8: SUIS - Before I get dressed to go out, I first visualize what I will look like if I wear different combinations of clothes.
SUIS_9: SUIS - When I think about a series of errands I must do, I visualize the stores I will visit.
SUIS_10: SUIS - When I first hear a friend’s voice, a visual image of him or her almost always springs to mind.
SUIS_11: SUIS - When I hear a radio announcer or DJ I’ve never actually seen, I usually find myself picturing what they might look like.
SUIS_12: SUIS - If I saw a car accident, I would visualize what had happened when later trying to recall the details.
